ith a wide range of issues, from tax policy to childcare, and includes the results of two innovative studies of public opinion on capital grants and inheritance tax. It is the first time that public opinion work has been integrated with theory into a serious and cohesive consideration of practical options for the future of asset-based welfare. The citizen's stake is accessibly written and aimed at a broad audience of academics, students and policy-makers. Indeed, anyone interested in how this new policy field can and should develop will want to read this book. The discussions are relevant to academics, researchers and policy makers overseas, particularly in the US, Canada, Australia, New Zealand, Germany, Ireland and Sweden, where there is a high level of interest in this topic.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aWelfare economics. 0aWelfare state. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / General.2bisacsh1 aAlstott, Anne L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBollier, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBoyes, Linda, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGamble, Andrew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGlennerster, Howard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLewis, Jane, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLewis, Miranda, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMaxwell, Dominic, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMaxwell, Dominic, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMcCormick, Jim, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcKnight, Abigail, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMc